@node REQ "MultiNotify Requirements"


 *  Workbench 2.0 or above.  (or Workbench 2.1 if you want the localization)


 *  @{" Triton.library " link THA} version 6 or more. (Distributed as release 2.0▀ or above)

@endnode



@node INS "MultiNotify Installation"


 *  Put  the  application  where you want.  (There is no 'Installer' script for
    this.   I think it is useless when the installation is done easier than the
    usage of the installation program...)


 *  The    catalog    for   the   desired   language   can   be   copied   into
    locale:catalogs/YourLanguage/  or  you  can create a catalogs/YourLanguage/
    directory  where  the  application resides and put the desired catalog into
    that  directory.  Note:  if you want to use the program in english there is
    no  need  to  install  a  catalog, since all the messages are by default in
    english.


 *  If  you  don't  already have @{" Triton.library " link THA} version 6 (Release 2.0) copy
    the one provided in the Ditribution directory into libs:  or move it in the
    directory  where  the  application  resides or use the provided 'Installer'
    installation   script.    Note  that  this  script  only  makes  a  minimal
    installation of Triton.  Here is the @{" Readme " link REA} of Triton.

@endnode



@node USE "MultiNotify Usage"


Press  the  'New'  button to add an item to the list.  An item called '<Empty>'
appears in the list.


You  can  now  set  the  path  and  filename  of the file you want to start the
notification  on.  This can be done by entering text in the string gadget or by
pressing  the  getfile button at right and using the asl-filerequester.  If the
'File:' string gadget is empty (i.e contains no character) then the notifcation
will be started on the directory entered in the path gadget.


You  can  set the command executed when a notification event appears entering a
command   in   the   string   gadget  'Execute:'  or  using  the  corresponding
asl-filerequester.   The  output  of  the commands are by default redirected to
NIL:  unless you specify a direction using the the '>' character.


@{u}Example 1:@{uu}

  Path:    's:'
  File:    'User-startup'
  Execute: 'Echo >con:20/20/300/50/NotifyEvent/WAIT/CLOSE "File is modified"'

    Here  you  can  be warned when an installation script (or maybe a virus...)
    modifies the User-Startup file...


@{u}Example 2:@{uu}

  Path:    'HD1:Programming/Projects/MyCurrentProject/Source'
  File:    'MyImportantFile.c'
  Execute: 'Execute s:doIncrBak
            HD1:Programming/Projects/MyCurrentProject/Source
            MyImportantFile.c'

    Where the file s:doIncrBak contains:

     .key DIR/A,FILE/A
     .bra {
     .ket }
      SetEnv Bk_{FILE} `Eval $Bk_{FILE}+1`
      Copy ENV:Bk_{FILE} ENVARC:
      Copy {DIR}/{FILE} SafePlace:{FILE}.$Bk_{FILE}

    Everytime   the   file   'HD1:Programming/Projects/MyCurrentProject/Source/
    MyImportantFile.c' is modified a backup of it is made to
    SafePlace:MyImportantFile.c.0 then to
    SafePlace:MyImportantFile.c.1 then to
    SafePlace:MyImportantFile.c.2 then to
    SafePlace:MyImportantFile.c.3 and so on...
    The counter is then stored in ENVARC:Bk_MyImportantFile.c.

    It  can  be  very useful for programmers who want to keep an history of the
    sources.   When a programmer introduces a bug in his code, he might want to
    see  where  the bug has been introduced in the source code.  And one of the
    best way is to see the old files...


Anytime  you  can  test  the  command  entered  in the @{b}'Execute:'@{ub} string gadget
pressing the 'Execute' button.


Anytime you can delete an entry in the list pressing the @{b}'Delete'@{ub} button.


Anytime  you  can  cancel  the  modifications of the list pressing the @{b}'Cancel'@{ub}
button.


If  you  use the @{b}'Hide'@{ub} button the window will be closed.  The changes won't be
deleted and the won't take effect now.


If  you use the @{b}'Use'@{ub} button the changes take effect immediately and the window
will be closed.


If you use the @{b}'Save'@{ub} button the changes take effect immediately, the window is
closed and the preferences are saved.


If  you  don't  want the help bubbles more delete the @{b}tooltype 'HELPBUBBLES'@{ub} in
the  icon  of  the  program.   If the program is runned from a command line the
tooltype won't take effect anyway.

@endnode



@node NOT "Things to be Aware of about notification"


 *  If  you  use the second example in the usage section, yo will have troubles
    with  the text editors which makes backup automatically (to #?.bak).  Since
    they  need  to  rename  the  file  to  #?.bak  and  then  write a new file,
    @{b}MultiNotify will receive several notification events.@{ub}

    For  example,  with  CygnusED you should use the 'Simple Saves' option else
    you will receive several Notification events and your command will be
    runned several times.


 *  The  Ram  Disk  has  a  little  bug  with the notification.  @{b}If you start a
    notification  on  a  file in 'Ram:' or in 'Ram Disk:' it simply won't work.@{ub}
    (The  program  will  accept  this, the notification will be started, but no
    message will be received.)

    But @{b}the notification@{ub} functions perfectly work on an @{b}Assign to the Ram Disk.@{ub}
    For example:
      Enter the following command:  Assign @{b}R:@{ub} Ram:
      And then start the notification on @{b}'R:MyFile'@{ub}  and this will work...

    This bug is still in the OS 3.1.


 *  Not all filesystems support the notification.  Most network filesystems and
    some  floppy  filesystems  won't  support  it.    The  FastFileSystem  from
    Commodore support the notification.    (So a floppy disk formatted with the
    FastFileSystem will support it.)

    If  you  want to create a mail box on a mulituser system,  you should start
    the  notification  on your hard drive and @{b}not@{ub} on a partition you see @{b}trough
    the network.@{ub}

    CrossDosFileSystem (PC-Disks) can't handle the notification.    (I think it
    isen't the most useful thing however...)

@endnode



@node ERR "MultiNotify Error messages."

The following errors messages may arrive.   Only those which aren't obvious are
documented:


    @{b}Oberon-A Error Handler... ...Halt program ! @{ub}

      This one must never arrive, else it is a bug in my program.
      If  it  arrives  write down the content of the message and send it to the
      @{" Author " link AUT}. If you can remember what happened send me a short description.


    @{b}Not enough memory.                        @{ub}


    @{b}Prefs file is corrupted:                  @{ub}

      Only MultiNotify must be used to edit the config file...


    @{b}Can't save configuration file:            @{ub}

      Disk error, disk full, disk write protected, file protected...


    @{b}Can't execute specified command:          @{ub}

      Command not found, not enough memory...


    @{b}Unable to save config to ENVARC:         @{ub}

      Disk error, disk full, disk write protected, file protected...


    @{b}Unable to save config to ENV:            @{ub}

      Disk error, disk full, disk write protected, file protected...


    @{b}Unable to load config from ENV:          @{ub}

      Disk error, file read protected or not found


    @{b}Internal Triton error:                   @{ub}

      Error  message  sent  by  triton.   The most probable cause is not enough
      memory


    @{b}Can't open version 6 of triton.library.
    This library must be installed in LIBS:
    or in the directory of the application.      @{ub}

      As it says...


    @{b}Can't initialize Triton interface:       @{ub}

      Perhaps  not  enough  space on the screen (shouldn't arrive),  not enough
      memory...


    @{b}Can't open asl.library:                  @{ub}

      You  can use MultiNotify but the asl-filerequester won't work.   You must
      then enter the files and commands manually.

@endnode



